"1323","1322":"1322","1320":"1320","1298":"1298","1375":"1375","about 1320":"circa 1320","1416":"1416","Gnosall, Staffordshire, England":"Gnosall, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Saint Lawrence Churchyard, Gnosall, Staffordshire, England":"Gnosall, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Crawley, Oxfordshire, England":"Crawley, Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Crawley Oxfordshire":"Crawley, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1320–1347":"1320–1347","1320–1375":"1320–1375","1322–Male":"1322–Deceased","1323–1382":"1323–1382","1336–1424":"1336–1424","1340–1416":"1340–1416","1295–1337":"1295–1337","1298–1325":"1298–1325","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1424":"1424","1336":"1336","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1320":"1320","1298":"1298","1375":"1375","about 1320":"about 1320","1416":"1416","Gnosall, Staffordshire, England":"Gnosall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Saint Lawrence Churchyard, Gnosall, Staffordshire, England":"Gnosall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Crawley, Oxfordshire, England":"Crawley, Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Crawley Oxfordshire":"Crawley, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Burgh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the ten English places named Burgh in northern England and East Anglia, or the six named Brough in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Westmorland, and Yorkshire. All these are from Old English <i>burg</i>, <i>burh</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘massive earthwork, fortification; manor, borough’. Compare   Bury  . The placename <i>Burgh</i> is pronounced as <i>borough</i>. The surname   Brough   arose equally from places now called Burgh and Brough, and is the more common form of the surname in modern Britain, where it is pronounced <i>bruff</i> or <i>broof</i> (/brʊf/). The Scottish surname was probably brought in from Yorkshire. For the surname in Ireland see   Burke  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Burke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Siobhan, Aileen, Brennan, Brigid, Donovan, Liam, Murphy, Ulick, Aidan, Dermot.","English and Irish (of Anglo-Norman origin): habitational name from Burgh (Castle) in Suffolk, England. <i>Burk</i> represents an Anglo-Norman pronunciation of Old English <i>burg</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘fortification’ (see   Burgh  ).","German: variant of   Burk  ."]},{"name":"Bury","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Bury in Lancashire (now part of Greater Manchester), or from some other similarly named place. The placename comes from the dative case, <i>byrig</i>, of Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified place’.","Walloon and French: habitational name from any of several places so named, in Wallonia (Belgium) and Oise (France). The placename is from <i>Buriacum</i>, the name of a Gallo-Roman estate, composed of the personal name <i>Burius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","South German: variant of   Buri  ."]},{"name":"Brough","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of various English places called Brough or Burgh. See   Burgh  .","Scottish: habitational name from Brough in Harray (Orkney).","Americanized form of German   Brauch   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Burrow","meanings":["English:","topographic name for someone who lived by a castle or manor house, or in a town, especially a chartered town or borough (Middle English <i>burgh</i>, Old English <i>burg</i> ‘fortified place, borough, manor’), or a habitational name for someone who came from a place so named because it was a fortified town or near an ancient fort, such as Burrow (Leicestershire, Lancashire), Burrough Green (Cambridgeshire), Brough (numerous counties), and Peterborough (Northamptonshire); see also   Burgh  .","topographic name for someone who lived on a hill or near a mound (Middle English <i>bergh</i>, Old English <i>beorg</i>), or a habitational name for someone who came from a place so named, such as Burrow (Devon, Somerset). Middle English <i>bergh</i> became throughly confused with <i>burgh</i> in 1 above. Compare   Burrough  ."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adam de Burgh was born in 1320, in Gnosall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William de Burgh, 1st Baron Burgh, was 25 and his mother, Lady Eleanor Cowley, was 22. He had at least 1 daughter with Alilitha de Harcourt. He died in 1347, in his hometown, at the age of 27, and was buried in Gnosall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1320–1347":"1320–1347","1320–1375":"1320–1375","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1323–1382":"1323–1382","1336–1424":"1336–1424","1340–1416":"1340–1416","1295–1337":"1295–1337","1298–1325":"1298–1325","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1424":"1424","1336":"1336","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1320":"1